{
  "status": "done",
  "comment": "## Design Spec\n\nCTO fallback: designer delegation did not produce a spec in time, so this spec is posted directly to keep [TES-16](/TES/issues/TES-16) moving.\n\n### Product Direction\n\n- Position the page as a modern Seiko 5 field-to-travel collection rather than a generic luxury-watch catalog\n- Tone should feel mechanical, collectible, and premium without imitating Swiss heritage language\n- Visual mood: dark graphite base, warm steel highlights, controlled bursts of Seiko sports color accents\n- No lead capture or forms; the page is a pure product story and showcase\n\n### Information Architecture\n\n- Hero: full-viewport introduction with strong headline, short supporting copy, and anchor CTA to the model grid\n- Credibility rail: 3 to 4 quick feature points that explain why Seiko 5 matters (automatic movement, durability, lume, value)\n- Models section: four-card showcase for SRPD55, SSK003, SRPG27, and SRPK87 with distinct positioning and specs\n- Comparison spotlight: horizontal or stacked comparison row surfacing use case, case feel, bezel/dial personality, and bracelet/strap styling\n- Brand-story section: short editorial block about the Seiko 5 legacy and why these references span everyday, travel, and field use\n- Detail strip: tactile specs or ownership cues such as movement, water resistance, lume, and day-date practicality\n- Closing section: collector-oriented signoff with a secondary anchor back to the models section; no form, no checkout, no newsletter\n\n### Layout And Composition\n\n- Keep a single-page narrative with generous vertical rhythm and alternating dense/light sections\n- Use a wide hero with copy pinned to one side and a layered watch composition or abstract watch-inspired graphic on the other\n- Avoid boxed SaaS-style sections; use edge-to-edge bands, asymmetrical grids, and inset panels to create motion\n- Model cards should feel editorial, not ecommerce-only: large product name, short descriptor, key spec line, and a strong visual treatment\n- Comparison area should break the repeated card rhythm with a different layout pattern so the page does not feel templated\n\n### Visual Direction\n\n- Palette: charcoal/black base, silver and champagne metal tones, off-white typography, restrained accent colors derived from model personalities\n- Suggested accents:\n  - SRPD55: gunmetal and warm orange\n  - SSK003: deep blue and red GMT accent\n  - SRPG27: olive/khaki field tone\n  - SRPK87: lighter neutral or champagne accent depending on available styling\n- Typography should feel intentional and less generic than Inter; use a condensed or industrial-feeling display face for major headings and a readable body face for supporting text\n- Surfaces should rely on gradients, radial highlights, thin strokes, and subtle grid/noise texture instead of flat cards on flat backgrounds\n\n### Content Guidance\n\n- Hero headline examples should speak to the versatility of Seiko 5 rather than generic prestige\n- Supporting copy should mention the collection spans sport, GMT travel, field utility, and modern daily wear\n- Each model entry should include:\n  - Reference number\n  - One-line identity statement\n  - 2 to 3 quick specs or usage cues\n  - A price/value framing line if used, but avoid fake pricing if no trusted source is present in-code\n- Keep copy concise and scannable; this is a landing page, not a long article\n\n### Model Positioning\n\n- SRPD55: urban sports reference, dark versatile daily wear, dive-style energy\n- SSK003: travel-oriented GMT with blue dial personality and more playful color accents\n- SRPG27: field-watch character, pragmatic readability, outdoors/everyday toughness\n- SRPK87: lighter modern variant that adds freshness and contrast to the lineup\n\n### Interaction And Motion\n\n- Add purposeful reveal motion on load for hero copy and watch cards\n- Use hover states that slightly shift lighting, border glow, or card elevation; avoid generic button bounce effects\n- If using CSS-only motion, keep it smooth and understated so the page still feels premium\n- Respect reduced-motion preferences\n\n### Responsiveness\n\n- Desktop: hero can split into two strong columns with staggered card layouts below\n- Tablet: collapse to simpler stacked sections while preserving the alternating visual rhythm\n- Mobile: prioritize headline readability, card spacing, and clear separation between the four references\n- Avoid fixed background attachments or effects that degrade on mobile\n\n### Accessibility\n\n- Maintain strong contrast on all text over textured or gradient backgrounds\n- Use semantic headings and list structures for specs/comparison content\n- Ensure CTA anchors remain descriptive even if there are only one or two on the page\n- Decorative watch visuals must not carry essential information without adjacent text\n\n### Implementation Guidance For DEV\n\n- Replace the current fictional luxury-watch content completely with Seiko 5-specific content and structure\n- Stay within the existing React/Vite single-page app unless a small component split materially improves clarity\n- Prefer local data objects for the four models so card/comparison sections are rendered consistently\n- Use CSS variables to define palette, spacing, typography, and section treatments up front\n- Create at least one layout pattern beyond a standard uniform card grid so the page feels designed rather than scaffolded\n- Keep external dependencies minimal; do not add a heavy animation library for simple reveal effects\n- Ensure the finished page passes lint, tests, and build, and provide a local preview command/result in the final handoff\n\n### Approval\n\n- This spec is approved for implementation and can be used as the source of truth for DEV."
}
